a 1432–1460","1432–1460":"1432–1460","1427–1474":"1427–1474","1454–1494":"1454–1494","1456–1568":"1456–1568","1458–1570":"1458–1570","1460–1497":"1460–1497","1410–Male":"1410–Overleden","1494":"1494","1 Jan 1460":"1 januari 1460","1460":"1460","1570":"1570","ABT 1458":"1458","1458":"1458","1568":"1568","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1497":"1497","1474":"1474","about 1453":"circa 1453","about 1432":"circa 1432","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, York, England,":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Thackley, Yorkshire, England":"Thackley, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1432–1460":"about 1432–1460","1432–1460":"1432–1460","1427–1474":"1427–1474","1454–1494":"1454–1494","1456–1568":"1456–1568","1458–1570":"1458–1570","1460–1497":"1460–1497","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1494":"1494","1 Jan 1460":"1 January 1460","1460":"1460","1570":"1570","ABT 1458":"1458","1458":"1458","1568":"1568","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1497":"1497","1474":"1474","about 1453":"about 1453","about 1432":"about 1432","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, York, England,":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Thackley, Yorkshire, England":"Thackley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bennett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the medieval personal name   Benedict  , from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. In the 12th century the Latin form of the name is found in England alongside versions derived from the Old French form <i>Beneit</i>, <i>Benoit</i>, which was common among the Normans. The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Bernhard  .","Altered form of French   Benet   or   Bennet   or of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennet","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  .","French: derivative of   Benne  ."]},{"name":"Bennitt","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennetts","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Bennett  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Dittus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":23,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Bennett was born about 1432, in Thackley, Yorkshire, England as the daughter of William Bennett Esq.. She married William Hutchinson Esq. about 1453, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1460, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1432–1460":"umbes 1432–1460","1432–1460":"1432–1460","1427–1474":"1427–1474","1454–1494":"1454–1494","1456–1568":"1456–1568","1458–1570":"1458–1570","1460–1497":"1460–1497","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1494":"1494","1 Jan 1460":"1. jaanuar 1460","1460":"1460","1570":"1570","ABT 1458":"1458","1458":"1458","1568":"1568","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1497":"1497","1474":"1474","about 1453":"umbes 1453","about 1432":"umbes 1432","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Cowlam, Yorkshire, E